[2
Date: Thu, 2 Apr 1998 10:04:41 -0600
From: Michelle O'Neill <oneill@uninet.net.mx>

I'm writing regarding your question of whether on not El Tor cholera should
be considered "real" cholera or just another generic diarrhea. I'm
assuming that the term "classical" used in the posting refers to _V.
cholerae_ O1 classical, and that "El Tor" refers to _V. cholerae_ O1 El
Tor.
There have been 8 pandemics caused by _V. cholerae_. _V. cholerae_ O1
classical was the cause of the first 6. _V. cholerae_ O1 El Tor is
responsible for the 7th pandemic which continues today, and _V. cholerae_
O139 is responsible for the 8th pandemic, which also continues today.
To my knowledge, Bangladesh is the only place where _V. cholerae_ O1
classical is still regularly isolated, and even there it only accounts for
a small percentages of the cases.
Considering that _V. cholerae_ O1 El Tor, and _V. cholerae_ O139 have
almost completely displaced _V. cholerae O1 classical, and that _V.
cholerae_ O1 El Tor is responsible for pandemic cholera, it is difficult to
accept Thailand's position that _V. cholerae_ O1 El Tor is not "real"
cholera.
Articles on Cholera in Thailand:
Bodhidatta et at. 1995. _Epidemiol. Infect._ 114:71-73
Hoge et al. 1996. _American J. of Epidemiology_ 143(3):263-268
--
Michelle O'Neill
Portland State University
e-mail: oneill@uninet.net.mx
